(42, 20, 7, 39, 2, 7, 9, NULL, 'Knowledge and Accountability in Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowledge and accountability in spiritual leadership. In Luke, the inability to discern the source of authority reflects a failure similar to the priests in Malachi, who have corrupted the law and led others astray.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 7, 43, 3, 19, 20, 'could not tell whence it was', 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowledge and ignorance. In Luke, the inability to discern the source reflects a preference for darkness, similar to John, where men love darkness over light due to their evil deeds.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 7, 43, 9, 39, 39, 'could not tell whence it was', 'Spiritual Blindness and Insight', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual perception. In Luke 20:7, the inability to discern the source reflects a lack of understanding, while John 9:39 contrasts this by discussing those who see and those who are blind.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 8, 18, 5, 12, 13, NULL, 'Authority and Craftiness', 'This connection highlights the theme of thwarting the plans of the crafty. In Luke, Jesus does not reveal his authority, paralleling Job''s assertion that God frustrates the devices of the crafty.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 8, 20, 26, 4, 5, NULL, 'Authority and Foolishness', 'This connection highlights the theme of responding wisely to challenges. In Luke, Jesus refrains from revealing his authority, paralleling Proverbs'' advice on how to engage with folly. Both passages emphasize discernment in communication.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 8, 40, 15, 14, 14, NULL, 'Authority and Blindness', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority and guidance. In Luke, Jesus does not reveal His authority, while in Matthew, He warns about blind leaders, suggesting a lack of true guidance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 8, 40, 16, 4, 4, NULL, 'Authority and Signs', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in both passages. In Luke, Jesus does not reveal His authority, while in Matthew, He critiques the demand for signs from a wicked generation, implying that true authority does not cater to such demands.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 8, 41, 11, 33, 33, 'by what authority I do these things', 'Authority of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' refusal to disclose his authority. This connection highlights a consistent theme of authority in his teachings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 8, 42, 22, 68, 68, NULL, 'Authority and Questioning', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of authority and the challenge of questioning. In Luke 20:8, Jesus refuses to disclose his authority, while in Luke 22:68, he anticipates that his question will not be answered, highlighting a tension in authority and response.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 9, 40, 21, 33, 46, 'planted a vineyard, and let it forth to husbandmen, and went into a far country', 'Vineyard Parable Connection', 'Both passages emphasize a vineyard planted by a man who goes into a far country, highlighting the theme of stewardship and accountability. The actions of the husbandmen in both parables illustrate a rejection of the owner''s authority and his messengers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 9, 41, 12, 1, 12, 'A certain man planted a vineyard', 'Parable of the Vineyard', 'Both passages emphasize a vineyard planted by a man and the actions of husbandmen. This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and the consequences of rejecting the owner''s messengers.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 9, 23, 5, 1, 7, 'a vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, representing God''s expectations and the resulting disappointment. The vineyard in Isaiah is a metaphor for Israel, while the vineyard in Luke serves as a parable about stewardship and accountability.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 9, 19, 80, 8, 14, 'planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, with Luke referencing a man who planted a vineyard and Psalms describing a vine brought out of Egypt. This connection highlights the cultivation and care of the vineyard, symbolizing a relationship between the owner and the land.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 9, 24, 2, 21, 21, 'planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of a vineyard representing God''s people. Both passages emphasize the idea of a planted vine, with Luke focusing on the vineyard''s caretakers and Jeremiah on the quality of the vine.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 9, 43, 15, 1, 8, 'a certain man planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard and True Vine Connection', 'This connection highlights the imagery of the vineyard and the role of the husbandman. Both passages emphasize the importance of fruitfulness and the relationship between the vine and its branches.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 9, 22, 8, 11, 12, 'let it forth to husbandmen', 'Vineyard Management Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard being entrusted to keepers or husbandmen. This connection highlights the responsibility of caretakers in managing what has been given to them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 10, 14, 36, 15, 16, 'sent a servant to the husbandmen', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of God''s messengers by the people. In Luke, the servant is beaten and sent away empty, while in 2 Chronicles, the messengers are mocked and despised.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 10, 16, 9, 26, 26, 'sent a servant', 'Rebellion Against God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of God''s servants. In Luke, the husbandmen beat the servant, paralleling the disobedience and violence against prophets in Nehemiah.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 10, 40, 21, 34, 36, 'sent a servant to the husbandmen', 'Servants Sent to Husbandmen', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of servants to the husbandmen to receive the fruits of the vineyard. They illustrate a pattern of rejection and violence against these servants by the husbandmen.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 10, 7, 6, 8, 10, 'sent a servant', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of a servant or prophet by God, who is met with rejection. This connection highlights the theme of disobedience and the consequences of not heeding God''s voice.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 10, 11, 22, 24, 24, 'sent a servant', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by God''s messengers. In both passages, the servants or prophets are met with hostility and violence, illustrating a consistent pattern of resistance to divine communication.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 10, 12, 17, 13, 13, 'sent a servant', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of God''s servants. In Luke, the husbandmen beat the servant sent to them, while in 2 Kings, the prophets sent by God are also disregarded. This connection highlights a recurring theme of disobedience to divine messengers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 10, 14, 16, 10, 10, 'sent him away empty', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of messengers sent by God. In Luke, the servant is beaten and sent away empty, while in 2 Chronicles, Asa oppresses the seer, indicating a similar theme of hostility towards divine communication.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 11, 28, 10, 1, 1, 'sent him away empty', 'Empty Vessels and Shameful Treatment', 'This connection highlights the theme of emptiness and unfruitfulness. In Luke, the servant is sent away empty, paralleling Israel''s depiction as an ''empty vine'' in Hosea, emphasizing their failure to produce true fruit.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
